First, we need to find the symmetric difference (A △ B) between sets A and B. The symmetric difference between two sets is the set of elements which are in either of the sets but not in their intersection.

A = {1, 2, 3, 4}
B = {2, 3, 4, 5}

Intersection of A and B (A ∩ B) = {2, 3, 4}

Now, we find the symmetric difference (A △ B):

Elements in A but not in (A ∩ B) = {1}
Elements in B but not in (A ∩ B) = {5}

So, A △ B = {1, 5}

Now, we need to find the symmetric difference between (A △ B) and {2, 3}:

(A △ B) = {1, 5}
C = {2, 3}

Intersection of (A △ B) and C = ∅ (empty set, since there are no common elements)

Elements in (A △ B) but not in C = {1, 5}
Elements in C but not in (A △ B) = {2, 3}

So, (A △ B) △ C = {1, 2, 3, 5}
